<body>
    <h1>Object Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Philosophy of Object Oriented Programming (OOP);</p></li>
<li>
<p>Advantages of OOP over structured programming;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Encapsulation, classes and objects, access specifiers, static and non-st=
atic members;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Constructors, destructors and copy constructors;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Array of objects, object pointers, and object references;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Inheritance: single and multiple inheritance;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Polymorphism: overloading, abstract classes, virtual functions and overr=
iding;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Exceptions; Object Oriented I/O;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Template functions and classes;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Multi-threaded Programming.</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Philosophy of Object Oriented Programming (OOP);</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Nice question =F0=9F=91=8D Let=E2=80=99s go deep into the <strong>Philos=
ophy of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CPhilosophyofObject-Ori=
entedProgramming(OOP)">=F0=9F=93=8C Philosophy of Object-Oriented Programmi=
ng (OOP)</h1>
<p>OOP is not just a programming style =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s a <strong>way=
 of thinking about problems</strong> by modeling them as <strong>objects</s=
trong> that represent real-world entities.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3CorePhilosophy"=
>1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Core Philosophy</strong></h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 The <strong>main idea</strong> of OOP is:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>=E2=80=9CProgram the way we think about the real world.=E2=80=9D</em=
></p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>
<p>In the real world, everything is an <strong>object</strong> (a car, a st=
udent, a bank account).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Each object has <strong>data (state)</strong> and <strong>behavior (acti=
ons/methods)</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>OOP tries to bring this <strong>real-world model</strong> into programmi=
ng.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3KeyPrinciplesof=
OOPPhilosophy">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Key Principles of OOP Philosophy=
</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B9a)Abstraction">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 a) <strong>Abstraction</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Focus on <strong>what an object does</strong>, not how it works internal=
ly.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>Car</strong> object has <code>start()</code>, <code>drive()</c=
ode>, <code>stop()</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>We don=E2=80=99t need to know how the engine works internally to use it.=
</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B9b)Encapsulation">=F0=
=9F=94=B9 b) <strong>Encapsulation</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Bundle <strong>data + methods</strong> together in one unit (object).</p=
></li>
<li>
<p>Hide internal details =E2=86=92 expose only necessary parts.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>BankAccount</strong> object hides the balance (private), but e=
xposes <code>deposit()</code> and <code>withdraw()</code>.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B9c)Inheritance">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 c) <strong>Inheritance</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Objects can <strong>reuse</strong> features of existing objects.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Car</code> and <code>Truck</code> inherit from <code>Vehicle</code=
>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>They share common properties but also have their own unique features.</p=
></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B9d)Polymorphism">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 d) <strong>Polymorphism</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>=E2=80=9COne interface, many forms.=E2=80=9D</p></li>
<li>
<p>Different objects can respond to the <strong>same message (method call)<=
/strong> in different ways.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Animal</code> has <code>speak()</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Dog.speak()</code> =E2=86=92 =E2=80=9CWoof=E2=80=9D</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Cat.speak()</code> =E2=86=92 =E2=80=9CMeow=E2=80=9D</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3WhyOOPPhilosoph=
yMatters">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Why OOP Philosophy Matters</strong></=
h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Models the real world naturally</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Code reusability</strong> (via inheritance, polymorphi=
sm)</p></li>
<li>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Maintainability</strong> (encapsulation hides complexi=
ty)</p></li>
<li>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Flexibility</strong> (objects can evolve without break=
ing everything)</p></li>
<li>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Scalability</strong> (large systems can be broken into=
 modular objects)</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AnalogyExample"=
>4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Analogy Example</strong></h2>
<p>Think of <strong>a University System</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Objects: <code>Student</code>, <code>Professor</code>, <code>Course</cod=
e>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Each has:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>State (attributes):</strong> <code>Student</code> =E2=86=92 name=
, id, GPA</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Behavior (methods):</strong> <code>enrollCourse()</code>, <code>=
calculateGPA()</code></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Relationships:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Professor</code> teaches <code>Course</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Student</code> enrolls in <code>Course</code>.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Inheritance:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>GraduateStudent</code> and <code>UndergraduateStudent</code> inher=
it from <code>Student</code>.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=E2=9C=85Summary">=E2=9C=85 Summar=
y</h2>
<p>The <strong>philosophy of OOP</strong> is about <strong>thinking in obje=
cts</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Objects =3D data + behavior</p></li>
<li>
<p>Encapsulation hides complexity</p></li>
<li>
<p>Inheritance reuses code</p></li>
<li>
<p>Polymorphism makes systems flexible</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 It=E2=80=99s a way to <strong>bridge human thinking about r=
eal-world entities with programming logic</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<p>Would you like me to also explain this with a <strong>diagram (real-worl=
d object =E2=86=92 class =E2=86=92 object in code)</strong> so it=E2=80=99s=
 easier to visualize?</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>Advantages of OOP over structured programming;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Great question =F0=9F=91=8D Let=E2=80=99s carefully compare <strong>Obje=
ct-Oriented Programming (OOP)</strong> vs <strong>Structured Programming (p=
rocedural)</strong> and highlight the <strong>advantages of OOP</strong>.</=
p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CAdvantagesofOOPoverStr=
ucturedProgramming">=F0=9F=93=8C Advantages of OOP over Structured Programm=
ing</h1>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ProgrammingAppr=
oach">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Programming Approach</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Structured Programming (Procedural)</strong> =E2=86=92</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Program is divided into <strong>functions/procedures</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Data and functions are <strong>separate</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: C language.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>OOP</strong> =E2=86=92</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Program is divided into <strong>objects (data + methods)</strong>.</p></=
li>
<li>
<p>Data and behavior are <strong>together</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: C++, Java, Python.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AdvantagesofOOP=
">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Advantages of OOP</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B91.Encapsulation(DataSe=
curity)">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. <strong>Encapsulation (Data Security)</strong></h3=
>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP bundles <strong>data + methods</strong> together in classes.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Internal details are <strong>hidden</strong> =E2=86=92 only necessary fu=
nctions are exposed.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming has <strong>global data</strong>, which is riskie=
r.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>In OOP, <code>BankAccount.balance</code> can be private. Only <code>depo=
sit()</code> / <code>withdraw()</code> methods can change it.</p></li>
<li>
<p>In structured programming, functions can directly modify global variable=
s.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B92.Reusability(Inherita=
nce)">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. <strong>Reusability (Inheritance)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP supports <strong>inheritance</strong> =E2=86=92 new classes reuse fe=
atures of existing ones.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming =E2=86=92 must <strong>re-write functions</strong=
> again and again.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Car</code> and <code>Bike</code> can inherit from <code>Vehicle</c=
ode>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Both reuse <code>start()</code> and <code>stop()</code> methods.</p></li=
>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B93.Flexibility(Polymorp=
hism)">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. <strong>Flexibility (Polymorphism)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP allows <strong>the same function name</strong> to work differently f=
or different objects.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming =E2=86=92 each function has to be written separat=
ely.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Animal.speak()</code> =E2=86=92 Dog says =E2=80=9CWoof=E2=80=9D, C=
at says =E2=80=9CMeow=E2=80=9D.</p></li>
<li>
<p>In procedural programming, you would need separate functions like <code>=
dogSpeak()</code>, <code>catSpeak()</code>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B94.Abstraction(HidingCo=
mplexity)">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. <strong>Abstraction (Hiding Complexity)</strong>=
</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP allows you to focus on <strong>what an object does</strong>, not how=
 it does it.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming =E2=86=92 often requires knowing how every functi=
on works.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>To drive a <strong>Car object</strong>, just call <code>car.drive()</cod=
e>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>You don=E2=80=99t need to know how the engine, fuel injection, or brakes=
 work.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B95.Modularity&amp;Maint=
ainability">=F0=9F=94=B9 5. <strong>Modularity &amp; Maintainability</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP programs are divided into <strong>independent objects</strong>.</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>Easier to <strong>debug, test, and update</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming =E2=86=92 functions are tightly coupled; harder t=
o maintain large systems.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B96.Scalability(LargePro=
jects)">=F0=9F=94=B9 6. <strong>Scalability (Large Projects)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP is better for <strong>large and complex systems</strong> (banking sy=
stems, ERPs, games).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming is suitable for <strong>small-scale programs</str=
ong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B97.Real-worldModeling">=
=F0=9F=94=B9 7. <strong>Real-world Modeling</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>OOP models programs closer to <strong>real-world entities</strong>.</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>Structured programming models everything as functions =E2=86=92 less int=
uitive.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ComparisonTable=
">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Comparison Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"f0=
673eb0-0fc6-454a-8725-f7bf8d6ea7fa" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Aspect</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Structured Programming (Procedural)</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Program Structure</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Functions/Procedures</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Classes &amp; Objects</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Data &amp; Functions</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Separate</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Combined (Encapsulation)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Reusability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Limited (copy-paste functions)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>High (Inheritance)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Flexibility</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Low</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>High (Polymorphism)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Complexity Handling</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Harder for large systems</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Easier (Abstraction &amp; Modularity)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Real-world Representation</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Weak</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Strong (objects map to entities)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Best suited for</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Small projects</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Medium to large systems</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=E2=9C=85Summary.1">=E2=9C=85 Summ=
ary</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Structured programming</strong> =E2=86=92 simple, function-drive=
n, good for small tasks.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>OOP</strong> =E2=86=92 modular, reusable, secure, scalable =E2=
=86=92 better for <strong>large, real-world systems</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 So the <strong>main advantages of OOP</strong> over structu=
red programming are:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Encapsulation</strong> =E2=86=92 security</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Inheritance</strong> =E2=86=92 reusability</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Polymorphism</strong> =E2=86=92 flexibility</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Abstraction</strong> =E2=86=92 simplicity</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Better scalability &amp; maintainability</strong></p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>Would you like me to also show this with a <strong>real example</strong>=
 (same problem solved in structured C style vs OOP style in C++/Java) for c=
larity?</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>Encapsulation, classes and objects, access specifiers, static and non-st=
atic members;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8D Let=E2=80=99s break down these <strong>OOP concepts=
</strong> clearly with examples.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CObject-OrientedProgram=
mingConcepts">=F0=9F=93=8C Object-Oriented Programming Concepts</h1>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Encapsulation">=
1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Encapsulation</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Encapsulation is the <strong>wrapping of data (attributes) and methods (=
functions) together in a single unit</strong> (class).</p></li>
<li>
<p>It also <strong>hides internal details</strong> and exposes only necessa=
ry parts via methods.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Benefits:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Data security (prevents unauthorized access)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Better maintainability</p></li>
<li>
<p>Control over data (validation before changing)</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example in Java:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class B=
ankAccount {
    private double balance; // private =E2=86=92 hidden from outside

    // Constructor
    BankAccount(double initialBalance) {
        balance =3D initialBalance;
    }

    // Public method to deposit money
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if(amount &gt; 0) balance +=3D amount;
    }

    // Public method to withdraw money
    public void withdraw(double amount) {
        if(amount &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; amount &lt;=3D balance) balance -=3D am=
ount;
    }

    // Public method to check balance
    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Here, <code>balance</code> is <strong>encapsulated</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Outside code cannot access it directly (<code>account.balance =3D 1000</=
code> would fail).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ClassesandObjec=
ts">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Classes and Objects</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-Class:"><strong>Class:</strong></h=
3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>blueprint/template</strong> for creating objects.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Defines <strong>attributes (state)</strong> and <strong>methods (behavio=
r)</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-Object:"><strong>Object:</strong><=
/h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>specific instance of a class</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Has its own copy of attributes.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">// Clas=
s definition
class Student {
    String name;
    int age;

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age);
    }
}

// Creating objects
Student s1 =3D new Student();
s1.name =3D "Alice";
s1.age =3D 20;
s1.display(); // Name: Alice, Age: 20

Student s2 =3D new Student();
s2.name =3D "Bob";
s2.age =3D 22;
s2.display(); // Name: Bob, Age: 22
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AccessSpecifier=
s">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Access Specifiers</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Access specifiers</strong> control <strong>visibility of class m=
embers</strong>.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"3b=
1f1e85-9161-43fa-91b5-0c0695f93e38" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Specifier</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Access Level</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>private</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Only within the same class</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>default</code> (no keyword)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Within the same package</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>protected</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Same package + subclasses</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>public</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Accessible from anywhere</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class E=
xample {
    private int privateVar;    // only inside class
    int defaultVar;            // same package
    protected int protectedVar; // subclass + package
    public int publicVar;       // anywhere
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3StaticandNon-St=
aticMembers">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Static and Non-Static Members</str=
ong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-StaticMembers:"><strong>Static Mem=
bers:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Belong to <strong>class</strong>, not to any object.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Shared across all objects of that class.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Accessed using <code>ClassName.memberName</code>.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-Non-StaticMembers:"><strong>Non-St=
atic Members:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Belong to <strong>individual object</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Each object has its own copy.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
ounter {
    static int count =3D 0; // static =E2=86=92 shared
    int id;               // non-static =E2=86=92 unique for each object

    Counter() {
        count++;        // increment shared counter
        id =3D count;     // assign unique id to object
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Object ID: " + id + ", Total count: " + count);
    }
}

// Test
Counter c1 =3D new Counter();
Counter c2 =3D new Counter();
c1.display(); // Object ID: 1, Total count: 2
c2.display(); // Object ID: 2, Total count: 2
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>count</code> is <strong>static</strong> =E2=86=92 shared between <=
code>c1</code> and <code>c2</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>id</code> is <strong>non-static</strong> =E2=86=92 unique for each=
 object.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=E2=9C=85Summary.2">=E2=9C=85 Summ=
ary</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"fc=
d574c7-8f72-4a13-a116-748130b57640" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Meaning / Use</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Encapsulation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Bundle data + methods, hide internal details</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Class</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Blueprint / template</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Object</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Instance of class</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Access Specifiers</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Control visibility: private, default, protected, public</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Static Members</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Belong to class, shared across objects</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Non-Static Members</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Belong to individual object, unique for each</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can <strong>draw a simple diagram</strong> showing <stron=
g>Class =E2=86=92 Objects + Static vs Non-Static Members + Encapsulation</s=
trong> to make it visually clear.</p>
