<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CObject-OrientedConcept=
s:Arrays,Pointers,andReferences">=F0=9F=93=8C Object-Oriented Concepts: Arr=
ays, Pointers, and References</h1>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ArrayofObjects"=
>1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Array of Objects</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>An <strong>array where each element is an object</strong> of a class.</p=
></li>
<li>
<p>Useful to <strong>store multiple objects together</strong> and access th=
em using an index.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    void display() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Name: " &lt;&lt; name &lt;&lt; ", Age: " &lt;&lt; ag=
e &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Array of 3 Student objects
    Student students[3];

    // Initialize objects
    students[0].name =3D "Alice"; students[0].age =3D 20;
    students[1].name =3D "Bob";   students[1].age =3D 22;
    students[2].name =3D "Carol"; students[2].age =3D 21;

    // Display all students
    for(int i =3D 0; i &lt; 3; i++)
        students[i].display();
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Point:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Each element is a <strong>full object</strong>, not just a reference.</p=
></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ObjectPointers"=
>2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Object Pointers</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>pointer that stores the address of an object</strong>.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Allows <strong>dynamic allocation</strong>, runtime polymorphism, and ef=
ficient object handling.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    void display() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Name: " &lt;&lt; name &lt;&lt; ", Age: " &lt;&lt; ag=
e &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Pointer to object
    Student *s =3D new Student();

    // Access members using pointer
    s-&gt;name =3D "Alice";
    s-&gt;age =3D 20;
    s-&gt;display();

    delete s; // free memory
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Use <code>-&gt;</code> to access members through pointer.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Can create <strong>array of object pointers</strong> dynamically.</p></l=
i>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example: Array of object pointers:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Student=
* students[3];
for(int i =3D 0; i &lt; 3; i++)
    students[i] =3D new Student(); // dynamic objects
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ObjectReference=
s">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Object References</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>reference is an alias for an existing object</strong>.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Cannot be <code>null</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Must be initialized at declaration.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    void display() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Name: " &lt;&lt; name &lt;&lt; ", Age: " &lt;&lt; ag=
e &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s1;
    s1.name =3D "Alice";
    s1.age =3D 20;

    // Reference to object
    Student &amp;ref =3D s1;

    ref.display(); // accesses s1
    ref.age =3D 21;  // modifies s1
    s1.display();  // Age: 21
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>References are <strong>aliases</strong>, not separate objects.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use <code>.</code> operator (like normal object) to access members.</p><=
/li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3QuickComparison=
Table">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Quick Comparison Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"cc=
bdf5cb-9c1a-4dd1-9f4e-07e07d2c5672" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Definition</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Syntax / Access</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Notes</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Array of Objects</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Array storing multiple <strong>objects</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>obj[i].member</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Each element is a full object</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Object Pointers</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Pointer storing <strong>address of an object</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>ptr-&gt;member</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Can use dynamic memory; access with <code>-&gt;</code></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Object References</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Alias for an existing object</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>ref.member</code></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Cannot be null; always refers to an object</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Summary:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Array of Objects</strong> =E2=86=92 multiple objects in fixed ar=
ray</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Object Pointers</strong> =E2=86=92 addresses, dynamic allocation=
, flexible</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Object References</strong> =E2=86=92 alias for existing objects,=
 easier syntax</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can also make a <strong>diagram showing Array of Objects,=
 Pointers, and References</strong> to make it visually clear how they diffe=
r in memory.</p>
