<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CPolymorphisminOOP">=F0=
=9F=93=8C <strong>Polymorphism in OOP</strong></h1>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Polymorphism means <strong>=E2=80=9Cone interface, many forms=E2=80=9D</=
strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>It allows objects of <strong>different classes</strong> to be treated as=
 objects of a <strong>common superclass</strong>, or <strong>methods with s=
ame name</strong> to behave differently.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Types of Polymorphism:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Compile-time (Static) Polymorphism</strong> =E2=86=92 Method/Ope=
rator Overloading</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Run-time (Dynamic) Polymorphism</strong> =E2=86=92 Virtual Funct=
ions &amp; Method Overriding</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Function/Method=
Overloading">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Function / Method Overloading</str=
ong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Same function name</strong> with <strong>different parameter lis=
ts</strong> in the <strong>same class</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Resolved at <strong>compile time</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Calculator {
public:
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
};

int main() {
    Calculator c;
    cout &lt;&lt; c.add(2, 3) &lt;&lt; endl;      // calls int version
    cout &lt;&lt; c.add(2.5, 3.5) &lt;&lt; endl;  // calls double version
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Point:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Same name, <strong>different parameters</strong> =E2=86=92 compile-time =
polymorphism</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AbstractClasses=
">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Abstract Classes</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A class that <strong>cannot be instantiated</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Used to <strong>define an interface</strong> for derived classes.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>Contains <strong>pure virtual functions</strong> (C++) / abstract method=
s (Java).</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Shape {
public:
    virtual void draw() =3D 0; // pure virtual function
};

class Circle : public Shape {
public:
    void draw() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Drawing Circle" &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Shape s; // ERROR: cannot instantiate abstract class
    Circle c;
    c.draw();
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Point:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Abstract class defines <strong>what</strong> a class should do, not <str=
ong>how</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3VirtualFunction=
s">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Virtual Functions</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A function in the <strong>base class</strong> that can be <strong>overri=
dden in derived class</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Declared with <code>virtual</code> keyword in C++.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Enables <strong>run-time polymorphism</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Vehicle {
public:
    virtual void start() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Vehicle starts" &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

class Car : public Vehicle {
public:
    void start() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Car starts" &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Vehicle *v =3D new Car();
    v-&gt;start();  // Run-time polymorphism: calls Car's start()
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Point:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Pointer or reference</strong> to base class calls <strong>derive=
d class method</strong> at runtime.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3MethodOverridin=
g">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Method Overriding</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Derived class</strong> provides a <strong>new implementation</st=
rong> of a function in <strong>base class</strong> with the same <strong>na=
me and parameters</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Requires <strong>inheritance</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class A=
nimal {
public:
    void speak() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Animal speaks" &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    void speak() {  // overrides base class method
        cout &lt;&lt; "Dog barks" &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Dog d;
    d.speak(); // Dog barks
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Difference from Overloading:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Overloading</strong> =E2=86=92 same class, different parameters =
(compile-time)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Overriding</strong> =E2=86=92 derived class changes base class m=
ethod (run-time with virtual function)</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3QuickSummaryTab=
le">5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Quick Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"bc=
bddf21-337e-46ad-9b40-9d6fd30662e9" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Key Idea</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example Usage</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Overloading</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Compile-time</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Same method name, different parameters</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>add(int a,b)</code> vs <code>add(double a,b)</code></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Abstract Class</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>N/A</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Cannot instantiate, contains pure virtual functions</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>Shape</code> class with <code>draw()</code></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Virtual Function</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Run-time</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Base class function that can be overridden</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>Vehicle::start()</code> virtual</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Overriding</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Run-time</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Derived class redefines base class method</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>Dog::speak()</code></p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In short:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Compile-time Polymorphism:</strong> Method/Operator overloading<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Run-time Polymorphism:</strong> Virtual functions + method overr=
iding + abstract classes</p></li>
<li>
<p>Makes code <strong>flexible, reusable, and maintainable</strong></p></li=
>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can also make a <strong>diagram showing Overloading vs Ov=
erriding vs Abstract Classes vs Virtual Functions</strong> so it=E2=80=99s =
easier to visualize.</p>
<p>Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"8">
<li>
<p>Exceptions; Object Oriented I/O;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect! Let=E2=80=99s carefully explain <strong>Exceptions</strong> and=
 <strong>Object-Oriented I/O (Input/Output)</strong> in C++ style.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CExceptionsinC++(ErrorH=
andling)">=F0=9F=93=8C <strong>Exceptions in C++ (Error Handling)</strong><=
/h1>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Exceptions are used to <strong>handle runtime errors</strong> in a progr=
am.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Instead of crashing, the program can <strong>catch and respond</strong> =
to errors gracefully.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Keywords:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>try</code> =E2=86=92 block of code to monitor for exceptions</p></=
li>
<li>
<p><code>throw</code> =E2=86=92 signal that an exception occurred</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>catch</code> =E2=86=92 block to handle the exception</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example (C++):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int a =3D 10, b =3D 0;

    try {
        if(b =3D=3D 0) {
            throw "Division by zero error!";
        }
        cout &lt;&lt; "Result: " &lt;&lt; a / b &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
    catch(const char* msg) {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Exception caught: " &lt;&lt; msg &lt;&lt; endl;
    }

    cout &lt;&lt; "Program continues..." &lt;&lt; endl;
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Code inside <code>try</code> is monitored.</p></li>
<li>
<p>If an exception occurs, control jumps to <code>catch</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Program continues after handling the exception.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=E2=9C=85AdvantagesofExceptions">=
=E2=9C=85 Advantages of Exceptions</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"14=
766187-29ae-4bd1-80c6-4761a3c884ed" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Advantage</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Explanation</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Clean error handling</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Avoids using return codes everywhere</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Separation of normal &amp; error code</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><code>try-catch</code> separates regular logic from error handling</p></=
td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Stack unwinding</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Automatically destroys local objects during exception propagation</p></t=
d>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Flexibility</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Different exception types can be caught separately</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CObject-OrientedI/O(OOP=
I/OinC++)">=F0=9F=93=8C <strong>Object-Oriented I/O (OOP I/O in C++)</stron=
g></h1>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>In C++, <strong>streams</strong> are objects used for input/output opera=
tions.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Part of <strong>iostream library</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Enables <strong>operator overloading</strong>, making I/O <strong>natura=
l with objects</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Key Streams:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>cin</code> =E2=86=92 standard input (keyboard)</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>cout</code> =E2=86=92 standard output (screen)</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>cerr</code> =E2=86=92 standard error (unbuffered)</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>clog</code> =E2=86=92 standard error (buffered)</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-Example:BasicI/OwithObjects"><stro=
ng>Example: Basic I/O with Objects</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    void input() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Enter name: ";
        cin &gt;&gt; name;
        cout &lt;&lt; "Enter age: ";
        cin &gt;&gt; age;
    }

    void display() {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Name: " &lt;&lt; name &lt;&lt; ", Age: " &lt;&lt; ag=
e &lt;&lt; endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.input();
    s.display();
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>I/O is <strong>object-oriented</strong>: <code>cin</code> and <code>cout=
</code> are objects of class <code>istream</code> and <code>ostream</code>.=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>You can <strong>overload </strong><code>&gt;&gt;</code><strong> and </st=
rong><code>&lt;&lt;</code><strong> operators</strong> for your classes to s=
upport custom I/O.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-Example:OverloadingI/OOperators"><=
strong>Example: Overloading I/O Operators</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">#includ=
e &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    // Overload &gt;&gt; for input
    friend istream&amp; operator&gt;&gt;(istream &amp;in, Student &amp;s) {
        cout &lt;&lt; "Enter name: ";
        in &gt;&gt; s.name;
        cout &lt;&lt; "Enter age: ";
        in &gt;&gt; s.age;
        return in;
    }

    // Overload &lt;&lt; for output
    friend ostream&amp; operator&lt;&lt;(ostream &amp;out, const Student &a=
mp;s) {
        out &lt;&lt; "Name: " &lt;&lt; s.name &lt;&lt; ", Age: " &lt;&lt; s=
.age;
        return out;
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    cin &gt;&gt; s;        // uses overloaded &gt;&gt;
    cout &lt;&lt; s &lt;&lt; endl; // uses overloaded &lt;&lt;
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Advantages of OOP I/O:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Cleaner syntax (<code>cin &gt;&gt; obj</code>, <code>cout &lt;&lt; obj</=
code>)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Custom I/O for objects possible using operator overloading</p></li>
<li>
<p>Consistent with C++ object-oriented design</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
