<h1 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=93=8CGenericsinJava">=F0=9F=
=93=8C <strong>Generics in Java</strong></h1>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Generics allow you to write <strong>type-safe, reusable code</strong> th=
at works with <strong>different data types</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Similar to C++ templates, but Java uses <strong>type parameters</strong>=
.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Generic Methods (Function Templates)</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Generic Classes (Class Templates)</strong></p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3GenericMethods"=
>1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Generic Methods</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A method that can operate on <strong>different types</strong> using a <s=
trong>type parameter</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">public =
class Main {

    // Generic method
    public static &lt;T&gt; T add(T a, T b) {
        // For demonstration, assuming T is Number
        return (T) (Double.valueOf(a.toString()) + Double.valueOf(b.toStrin=
g()));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(add(5, 10));         // Integer
        System.out.println(add(2.5, 3.5));      // Double
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>&lt;T&gt;</code> declares a <strong>type parameter</strong>.</p></=
li>
<li>
<p><code>T</code> can be <strong>Integer, Double, String</strong>, etc., de=
pending on usage.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-=F0=9F=94=B9GenericMethodwithMulti=
pleTypeParameters">=F0=9F=94=B9 Generic Method with Multiple Type Parameter=
s</h3>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">public =
class Main {

    public static &lt;T, U&gt; void display(T a, U b) {
        System.out.println(a + " and " + b);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        display(10, "Hello");  // T=3DInteger, U=3DString
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ObjectOrientedProgramming(OOP)-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3GenericClasses"=
>2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 <strong>Generic Classes</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A class with <strong>type parameters</strong> that can work with multipl=
e types.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">// Gene=
ric class
class Box&lt;T&gt; {
    private T content;

    public void setContent(T content) {
        this.content =3D content;
    }

    public T getContent() {
        return content;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box&lt;Integer&gt; intBox =3D new Box&lt;&gt;();
        intBox.setContent(123);
        System.out.println("Int Box: " + intBox.getContent());

        Box&lt;String&gt; strBox =3D new Box&lt;&gt;();
        strBox.setContent("Hello");
        System.out.println("String Box: " + strBox.getContent());
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Key Points:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Box&lt;Integer&gt;</code> =E2=86=92 works with Integer</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Box&lt;String&gt;</code> =E2=86=92 works with String</p></li>
<li>
<p>Same class works for <strong>any type safely</strong></p></li>
</ul>
